Hi @harikrishnac!

If you mean upon initialization, then set the pager [`page` option](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#pager-page) to `2` (zero-based index)

```js
$(function() {
  $("#searchResultsID")
    .tablesorter()
    .tablesorterPager({
      // other options...
      page : 2
    };
});
```

And set a [`data-value` attribute](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/example-widget-filter.html#methods) with the initial filter search in the selected column header.

```html
<th data-value="spiders">phobias</th>
```

If you want to set the page and filter after initialization, or if the user clicks a button, or something, then use the following code:

```js
var $table = $('table');
// set filters, but do not apply them to prevent more than one server call
$.tablesorter.setFilters( $table, [ '', '', 'spiders', '', '', '' ], false );
// go to page 3 - pass a one-based index!
$table.trigger('pageSet', 3);
```

NOTE 1: See the [`setFilters` method](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#function-setfilters) for reference - the docs need to be updated, leaving off the `false` parameter, as of v2.24.3, will now default to `true` and apply the filter.
NOTE 2: The [`pageSet` method](http://mottie.github.io/tablesorter/docs/#pageset) uses a "one-based" index!

