I don't agree with this behavior being normal. Having to wrap these calls with home-made recursive conversion functions goes against the principle that you can usually just pass a boto resource around. It should be usable as-is.

I understand that python floats are annoying and unprecise, but boto really should handle the extra step of handling these conversions for the user. I agree that it shouldn't allow Inexact conversions, but for this it would be better to allow the user to attach his own conversion function when Inexact is raised.

I had to do something similar to this in the past.

Property collectors took me a bit of time to grasp. Here's how I think how its composed of each of its components:
- `TraversalSpec` defines how to traverse a managed object type to get to other managed object. In other words, it is used to bring more managed objects into the scope of your property collector.
- `ObjectSpec` defines a managed object that you start at.
- `PropertySpec` defines what properties of a managed object to collect (the data you're actually trying to get). It can only collect data from paths that reference a `DataObject` or a field containing a primitive data type. If you reference a path to a `ManagedObject` it will collect its `Managed Object ID (moid)`.

With all that in mind, it seems that you can't have a `PropertySpec` for a `VirtualMachine`  that will go across to a its `parent`, be it `Folder` or `Host`, to collect its name.

The issue is that `PropertyCollector` only provides a normalized view of the data. What you are trying to do is denormalize the data. I ended up having to fetch all the relevant managed objects and then building a denormalized view on top of that.

The approach I took:
- Collect all managed objects and their local properties (including properties linking to another managed object by id)
- Create a mapping from `<managed object type>-<managed object id>` to its local properties.
- Create denormalized view on top of this map.

Here's a rough example illustrating the data transformation:
``
# map built from data returned by PropertyCollector
obj_db = {
    'vim.VirtualMachine:vm-65': {
        'name': 'my cool vm',
        'parent': 'vim.HostSystem:host-99',
    },
   'vim.HostSystem:host-99': {
        'name': 'my host',
  }
}

def denormalize_vm(moid, data):
    return {
        'name': data['name'],
        'host': obj_db[data['parent']]['name'],
   }

vms = filter(lambda k, _: k.startswith('vim.VirtualMachine'), obj_db))
denormalized_vms = map(denormalize_vm, vms)                                            
```

